<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="171" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="10.[1401,2607,2941,3484]" pageId="10" pageNumber="171">
Recent comprehensive molecular phylogenetic analysis showed that M. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Major" authorityYear="1896" box="[2410,2498,2979,3012]" class="Mammalia" family="Tenrecidae" genus="Microgale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Afrosoricida" pageId="10" pageNumber="171" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pusilla">pusilla</taxonomicName>
is sister to a clade of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goodman &amp; Soarimalala" authorityYear="2004" box="[1583,1746,3018,3051]" class="Mammalia" family="Tenrecidae" genus="Microgale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Afrosoricida" pageId="10" pageNumber="171" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="jenkinsae">M. jenkinsae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1882" box="[1763,1976,3018,3051]" class="Mammalia" family="Tenrecidae" genus="Microgale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Afrosoricida" pageId="10" pageNumber="171" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="longicaudata">M. longicaudata</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1918" box="[1993,2120,3018,3051]" class="Mammalia" family="Tenrecidae" genus="Microgale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Afrosoricida" pageId="10" pageNumber="171" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="majori">M. majori</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1926" box="[2199,2379,3018,3051]" class="Mammalia" family="Tenrecidae" genus="Microgale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Afrosoricida" pageId="10" pageNumber="172" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="principula">M. principula</taxonomicName>
. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1402,2142,3058,3091]" pageId="10" pageNumber="171" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6808302" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6808302" box="[1402,2142,3058,3091]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6808302/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="171" targetBox="[1398,1989,2519,2932]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph blockId="10.[1401,2607,2941,3484]" box="[1402,2142,3058,3091]" pageId="10" pageNumber="171">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1402,1577,3058,3091]" pageId="10" pageNumber="171">Distribution.</emphasis>
Central Highlands, E &amp; SE Madagascar.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="171" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[1401,2607,2941,3484]" pageId="10" pageNumber="171">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1402,1651,3097,3130]" pageId="10" pageNumber="171">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 51-63 mm,tail 62-85 mm, ear 8-13 mm, hindfoot 11-13 mm; weight 3-5 g. The Least Shrew 
<taxonomicName box="[1949,2046,3137,3170]" class="Mammalia" family="Tenrecidae" genus="Tenrec" kingdom="Animalia" order="Afrosoricida" pageId="10" pageNumber="171" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Tenrec</taxonomicName>
is very small, and tail is long, 130-160% of head-body length. Dorsal pelage is soft and grizzled reddish brown, and venteris gray, with a buffy wash.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="171" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[1401,2607,2941,3484]" pageId="10" pageNumber="171">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1402,1513,3255,3288]" pageId="10" pageNumber="171">Habitat.</emphasis>
Humid forests (tolerant of some disturbance) and wet grasslands to marshy habitats at elevations of 530-1670 m (but recently documented at higher elevations).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
